declarations.comments:
Type-level path representation

Examples:
  Path Root                               -- /
  Path (Lit "users")                      -- /users
  Path (Lit "users" / Capture "id" Int)  -- /users/:id
  Path (Lit "users" / Capture "id" Int / Lit "posts")  -- /users/:id/posts
declarations.title: Path

declarations.comments:
Root path representing "/"

Example:
  Path Root  -- /
declarations.title: Root

declarations.comments:
Literal path segment (wrapper for Symbol to work around PureScript 0.15 limitations)

In PureScript 0.15, we can't use bare Symbols like Path "users" due to kind inference.
Instead, use: Path (Lit "users")

Example:
  Path (Lit "users")                     -- /users
  Path (Lit "users" / Capture "id" Int)  -- /users/:id
declarations.title: Lit

declarations.comments:
Capture a path parameter with a name and type

Example:
  Capture "id" Int    -- captures :id as an Int
  Capture "name" String  -- captures :name as a String
declarations.title: Capture

declarations.comments:
Infix operator for building paths

Example:
  Lit "users" / Capture "id" Int / Lit "posts"
declarations.title: type (/)

declarations.comments:
Sugar for Capture  use with bare Symbols in the path DSL

Example:
  Path ("users" / "id" : Int / "posts")
  -- equivalent to: Path (Lit "users" / Capture "id" Int / Lit "posts")
declarations.title: Param
QueryParams

declarations.comments:
Marker for required query parameters (default is optional  Maybe)

Example:
  Path ("users") :? (limit :: Int, offset :: Required Int)
  -- limit parses as Maybe Int, offset parses as Int (fails if missing)
declarations.title: Required

declarations.comments:
Generate a Fastify-compatible URL pattern from a path type

Examples:
  pathPattern (Proxy :: _ (Path Root)) = "/"
  pathPattern (Proxy :: _ (Path (Lit "users"))) = "/users"
  pathPattern (Proxy :: _ (Path (Lit "users" / Capture "id" Int))) = "/users/:id"
  pathPattern (Proxy :: _ ("users" / "id" : Int)) = "/users/:id"
declarations.title: PathPattern

declarations.comments:
Define an OpenAPI link to express relationships between operations.
Links allow you to indicate how values from one operation's response can be used
as parameters in another operation.

Parameters:
  inner - The wrapped type (transparent wrapper)
  linkName - The link identifier (e.g., "getUser")
  operationId - The target operation ID to link to
  parametersRow - A row of parameter mappings with runtime expressions (as Symbol types)

Example:
  ok :: { body :: User }
    # Link "deleteUser" "deleteUserById" ( userId :: "$response.body#/id" )
declarations.title: Link

declarations.comments:
Define an OpenAPI callback for webhook/asynchronous API patterns.
Callbacks allow you to define outgoing requests that your API will make to the client.

Parameters:
  inner - The wrapped type (transparent wrapper)
  name - The callback identifier (e.g., "onPaymentComplete")
  expression - The URL with runtime expressions (e.g., "{$request.body#/callbackUrl}")
  method - The HTTP method type for the callback (GET, POST, etc.)
  requestBody - The request body type for the callback
  responseRow - The response variants row for the callback

Example:
  type PaymentRoute = Route POST (Path (Lit "payment"))
    (Request { body :: JSON PaymentRequest })
    ( ok :: { body :: PaymentResponse }
    ) # Callback "onPaymentComplete" "{$request.body#/callbackUrl}" POST
        (JSON { status :: String, transactionId :: String })
        ( ok :: { body :: { received :: Boolean } } )
declarations.title: Callback

    ) # Callback "onPaymentComplete" "{$request.body#/callbackUrl}" POST
        (JSON { status :: String, transactionId :: String })
        ( ok :: { body :: { received :: Boolean } } )
declarations.title: Callback

declarations.comments:
Define an OpenAPI link to express relationships between operations.
Links allow you to indicate how values from one operation's response can be used
as parameters in another operation.

Parameters:
  inner - The wrapped type (transparent wrapper)
  linkName - The link identifier (e.g., "getUser")
  operationId - The target operation ID to link to
  parametersRow - A row of parameter mappings with runtime expressions (as Symbol types)

Example:
  ok :: { body :: User }
    # Link "deleteUser" "deleteUserById" ( userId :: "$response.body#/id" )
declarations.title: Link

declarations.comments:
Attach multiple named examples to a type for OpenAPI documentation.
This allows you to provide several example values that will appear in the
generated OpenAPI spec.

Example:
  Int # Examples (basic :: ExampleValue "42", advanced :: ExampleValue "100")
declarations.title: Examples

declarations.comments:
A simple example with just a value (used in Examples row).

Example:
  basic :: ExampleValue "42"
declarations.title: ExampleValue

declarations.comments:
An example with a summary (used in Examples row).

Example:
  premium :: ExampleWithSummary "456" "Premium user"
declarations.title: ExampleWithSummary

declarations.comments:
A complete example object with value, summary, description, and optional externalValue.

Example:
  external :: ExampleObject "" "External example" "An example from URL" "https://example.com/data.json"
declarations.title: ExampleObject

declarations.comments: Type for extracted link metadata
declarations.title: LinkMetadata

declarations.comments: Render HTTP method to lowercase string (OpenAPI format)
declarations.title: RenderMethod

declarations.comments:
Response data combining headers and body
This is a data type (not type alias) to work with type class instances
declarations.title: Response

declarations.comments: Deprecated alias for backwards compatibility
declarations.title: ResponseData

declarations.comments:
Convert user-friendly record syntax to Response type.

Supports:
  Response headers body  Response headers body (identity)
  { body :: User }  Response () User
  { headers :: { "Location" :: String }, body :: User }  Response ("Location" :: String) User
declarations.title: ToResponse

contents.contents: Do not include 'status', 'statusCode', or other fields.

declarations.comments:
RowList-based helper to distinguish records with/without headers.
Instance heads are distinguishable by the RowList structure.
declarations.title: ToResponseRL

declarations.comments:
Construct a variant response with full control over headers and body

Example:
  respond (Proxy :: _ "created")
    (Response { headers: { "Location": "/users/123" }, body: user })
declarations.title: respond

declarations.comments:
Construct a variant response with separate headers and body arguments

Example:
  respondWith (Proxy :: _ "created")
    { "Location": "/users/123" }
    user
declarations.title: respondWith

declarations.comments:
Construct a variant response with no custom headers (most common case)

Example:
  respondNoHeaders (Proxy :: _ "ok") user
  respondNoHeaders (Proxy :: _ "notFound") { error: "Not found" }
declarations.title: respondNoHeaders

declarations.comments:
Construct a variant response using numeric status code

Example:
  respondStatus @200 user
  respondStatus @404 { error: "Not found" }
declarations.title: respondStatus

declarations.comments:
Construct a variant response with headers using numeric status code

Example:
  respondStatusWith @201 { "Location": "/users/123" } user
declarations.title: respondStatusWith

declarations.comments:
Construct a variant response with headers but no body

Example:
  respondNoBody (Proxy :: _ "noContent")
    { "X-Resource-Id": "123" }
declarations.title: respondNoBody

declarations.comments:
Construct a variant response with neither headers nor body

Example:
  respondNothing (Proxy :: _ "noContent")
  respondNothing (Proxy :: _ "notModified")
declarations.title: respondNothing

declarations.comments:
Construct a 204 No Content response (no headers, no body)

Example:
  respondNoContent
declarations.title: respondNoContent

declarations.comments:
Construct a 304 Not Modified response (no headers, no body)

Example:
  respondNotModified
declarations.title: respondNotModified

declarations.comments:
Convert a variant row with record syntax to Response types.
Input: ( ok :: { body :: User }, notFound :: { body :: ErrorMsg } )
Output: ( ok :: Response () User, notFound :: Response () ErrorMsg )
declarations.title: ConvertResponseVariant

declarations.comments:
A handler tied to a specific route type.

Usage:
  userHandler :: Handler UserRoute
  userHandler = mkHandler \{ path } -> ...
declarations.title: Handler

declarations.comments: Type class that computes the handler function type from a Route type.
declarations.title: RouteHandler

declarations.comments: Create a Handler from a function matching the route's type.
declarations.title: mkHandler

declarations.comments: Extract the handler function from a Handler.
declarations.title: runHandler

declarations.comments: Map variant constructor names (Symbols) to HTTP status codes
declarations.title: StatusCodeMap

contents.contents: 2xx Success: ok, created, accepted, noContent, etc.
3xx Redirect: movedPermanently, found, seeOther, notModified, etc.
4xx Client: badRequest, unauthorized, forbidden, notFound, conflict, unprocessableEntity, etc.

declarations.comments: Internal class that matches on Proxy types to avoid overlapping instances
declarations.title: StatusCodeMapImpl

declarations.comments: Convert StatusCode to String for OpenAPI generation
declarations.title: statusCodeToString

declarations.comments: Map numeric status codes to their label names
declarations.title: StatusCodeToLabel
